{#
    Custom index template — shows the project __init__.py docstring as the main page
    instead of a bare module list or an automatic redirect.
#}
{% extends "default/frame.html.jinja2" %}

{% block title %}PythonDiscreteControl – API Documentation{% endblock %}

{% block style %}
    {{ super() | safe }}
    <style>
        header.pdoc {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            flex-wrap: wrap;
            margin-bottom: 1rem;
        }
        header.pdoc input[type=search] {
            outline-offset: 0;
            font-size: 1.5rem;
            min-width: 60%;
            flex-grow: 1;
            padding-left: .5rem;
            margin: 1.75rem 0;
        }
    </style>
{% endblock %}

{% block nav %}
    <h2>Modules</h2>
    <ul>
        {% for submodule in all_modules if "._" not in submodule and not submodule.startswith("_") %}
            <li><a href="{{ submodule.replace(".", "/") }}.html">{{ submodule }}</a></li>
        {% endfor %}
    </ul>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
    <header class="pdoc">
        {% if search %}
            <input type="search" placeholder="Search API Documentation…" aria-label="search box">
        {% endif %}
    </header>

    <main class="pdoc">
        <article class="pdoc">

            <h1>Hybrid Control and Simulation Library for Discrete–Continuous Systems</h1>

            <p>This library provides a unified framework for simulating control systems that combine
            discrete-time controllers with continuous-time or discretised plant models.</p>

            <p>The main goal is to support consistent comparison between:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Pure discrete-time transfer function simulations (z-domain models)</li>
                <li>Continuous-time state-space simulations with numerical integration</li>
                <li>Hybrid closed-loop systems where a discrete controller interacts with a continuous plant</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Core Features</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Discrete-time signal simulation</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Finite-difference implementation of transfer functions</li>
                        <li>Used for controllers (PID, RST) and discrete plant models</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Continuous-time plant simulation</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>State-space representation (A, B, C matrices)</li>
                        <li>Numerical integration via RK4</li>
                        <li>Used for high-fidelity plant dynamics</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Hybrid simulation environment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Discrete controller evaluated at a fixed sampling period</li>
                        <li>Continuous plant updated at a finer integration timestep</li>
                        <li>Emulates real digital control hardware interacting with a physical system</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Control architectures</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>PID controllers implemented as discrete transfer functions</li>
                        <li>RST controllers using polynomial representations (R, S, T)</li>
                        <li>Unified interface for future extensions (LQR, MPC, …)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <h2>Architecture Overview</h2>
            <p>The library is structured around five abstraction layers:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Simulation</strong> — numerical evolution of systems:
                    <code>TFSimulator</code>, <code>HybridSim</code>, <code>NonLinearHybridSim</code>;
                    high-level runner functions in <code>runners.py</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Control</strong> — discrete controllers:
                    <code>DiscretePID</code>, <code>RSTController</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Models</strong> — physical parameters and plant representations:
                    <code>ballbeam_config</code>, <code>LinearStateSpaceModel</code>,
                    <code>TransferFunctionModel</code>, <code>NonlinearBallBeamModel</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Metrics_Plotting</strong> — logging, plotting, and performance metrics:
                    <code>SimLog</code>, <code>Plotting</code>, <code>Metrics</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Utils</strong> — helper functions:
                    CSV export (<code>as_csv</code>), RST synthesis
                    (<code>Compute_Desired_RST</code>, <code>Compute_Denominator_Matching_RST</code>),
                    pole placement utilities.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Design Philosophy</h2>
            <p>The library is designed to ensure consistency between:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Analytical control design (transfer functions, z-domain algebra)</li>
                <li>Numerical simulation (difference equations and integration methods)</li>
                <li>Hybrid digital implementations (realistic sampled-data control loops)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>A key objective is to make discrepancies between theoretical models, numerical
            simulation, and hybrid execution <em>explicit and measurable</em> rather than hidden.
            This enables systematic validation of discretisation effects, sampling-time influence,
            numerical integration errors, and controller implementation consistency.</p>

        </article>
    </main>

    {% if search %}
        {% include "search.html.jinja2" %}
    {% endif %}
{% endblock %}
